###############################################################################
### MINITASK

It's a miniature multi-tasking operating system for the Arduino Nano, which is
a little computer-on-a-chip.
See also:
* https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arduino

The purpose of this project is to let me experiment with the Arduino from my
laptop, examining its memory on the fly, and sending it little programs to run,
either as one-off commands or as concurrent tasks, with observable behaviour
like toggling LEDs and sending bytes back over USB etc.
Basically, it's a way to learn about embedded programming and realtime OS
implementation.

The core system (the multi-tasking OS) is written in C and assembly, using the
standard AVR development toolchain: avr-gcc, avr-libc, avrdude, etc.
See also:
* https://www.nongnu.org/avr-libc/
* https://github.com/avrdudes/avr-libc
* https://github.com/avrdudes/avrdude

The core of the OS (scheduler, resource queues, etc) is written in C.

The commands/tasks you send to the OS use a tiny programming language, let's
call it "tasklang", written in assembly.

The client (which runs on my/your laptop, and talks to the OS over USB) is
written in Python.


###############################################################################
### TASKLANG

The "minitasks" system consists of a Python client sending little programs
over USB to the OS on the Arduino, to be run as tasks.
These little programs are written in a language called "tasklang".

The language is vaguely FORTH-like: it's explicitly stack-based, and uses
"threaded code" as its execution model, that is, "code" consists of arrays of
pointers representing subroutine calls.
However, unlike FORTH, tasklang doesn't come with its own compiler; instead,
programs are compiled by the Python client, and the OS only needs to know how
to run them.
See also:
* https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forth_(programming_language)
* https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Threaded_code

The language is very simple: everything is an integer, integers can also be
interpreted as pointers, all variables are global, and there is currently
no way to define functions (so, all function calls are to built-in
functions, implemented in assembly).

However, the purpose of the language isn't to be expressive, but to be easy
to reason about and debug, and just powerful enough to play with multitasking
concepts like scheduling, resources, and inter-task communcation.

Here's an example program, which does some math and then ends:

    # Set x to 1 + 2.
    # The "1" and "2" literals push their values onto the stack.
    # The "+" operator pops 2 values off the stack, adds them together,
    # and pushes the result onto the stack.
    # For more information, read any basic FORTH tutorial!..
    # As for "=x", that's not standard FORTH syntax: it means "pop a value
    # from the stack and store it in the x variable".
    1 2 + =x

    # Set y to x * x.
    # The meaning of "dup" is "duplicate the value on top of the stack", so
    # "x dup" is equivalent to "x x".
    x dup * =y

    # Assert that x equals 3, and y equals 9.
    # If an assertion fails, the task is stopped, but hangs around in memory
    # so you can inspect it if you want.
    x 3 == assert
    y 9 == assert

Here's another example program, which runs as a long-lived task.
Its behaviour is to blink the Arduino's built-in LED on and off, once per
second:

    # Set the variable "led_state" to 0
    0 =led_state

    # Start an infinite loop
    loop {
        # Call the set_led function with one argument, the desired LED state
        # (0 for off, 1 for on)
        led_state set_led

        # Reverse the desired LED state
        led_state ! =led_state

        # Ask the OS to put this task to sleep & wake it up in 1 second
        sleep 1000
    }

Here's another example program.
NOTE: Running a program creates a task with at least two associated byte
streams: stdin and stdout (standard input/output).
Streams can be hooked up directly to the Arduino's USB port, i.e. the Python
client, or they can be hooked up to other tasks.

    # Set msg to point at the current top of the heap.
    # Every task has a stack and a heap, which grow towards each other.
    # All variables are 16-bit integers, which can also be interpreted as
    # as pointers.
    heap =msg

    loop {
        # Call getc, putting this task to sleep & waking it up once a
        # byte is available on its stdin
        getc =c

        # Push c onto the heap as a single byte
        c hpushc

        # If c was a NUL byte, exit the loop
        c while
    }

    # At this point, msg points to a C-style string on the heap!..
    # Now we're going to repeatedly echo it back over stdout.
    # For fun, we'll keep track of how many times we echo it.
    0 =n_echoes

    loop {

        # Set ptr to msg, i.e. the start of the string
        msg =ptr

        # Loop over the characters in the string
        loop {
            # Dereference ptr, getting a byte, and store that in c
            ptr $c =c

            # Break on NUL byte
            c while

            # Call putc, putting c in this task's stdout buffer, then
            # putting this task to sleep & waking it up once the byte has
            # been consumed
            c putc

            # Increment ptr
            ptr 1+ =ptr
        }

        # Increment our echo counter
        n_echoes 1+ =n_echoes

        # Logging is sent directly through the USB to the Python client,
        # using low-level assembly routines.
        # That is, tasks don't have a separate stderr stream, rather logging
        # is atomic and bypasses the OS.
        # Why?.. because logging is for debugging purposes, of course!
        # It would be harder to debug the OS if logging was tied up with it...
        # Anyway, if we want to log a dynamic message, we don't build a string
        # on the heap!.. we log it in parts.
        # We can use an atomic block to make sure other tasks don't log (or do
        # anything else) while we're logging.
        atomic {
            "Echoed " logs
            msg logs
            ' ' logc
            n_echoes logi
            " times!\n" logs
        }
    }

